Where the creditor agreed by pactum de non petendo not to sue one of two or more correi debendi, the other or rest could take advantage ol the pactum only if, as it is said, it was in rem (see on Blr. iv. 14. 4 ini), even though partners of the other, Dig. 2. 14. 25. 2, ‘multum enirn interest, utrum res ipsa solvatur, an persona liberetur' Dig. 45. 2. 19, ‘in rem pacta omnibus prosunt, quorum obligationem dissolutam esse eius, qui paciscebatur, interluit' Dig. 2. 14. 25. 5. Hence the pactum de non petendo in rem osone correus debendi benefits the rest whenever on payment by one ol them he would have regressus against the others, for otherwise the pactum would be practically inoperative. But if, conversely, one ol two or more correal creditore concluded a pactum de non petendo with their joint debtor, the latter could in no case plead it in defence to an action instituted by the other or others: ¹ si unus ex argentariis sociis cum debitore pactus sit, an etiarn alteri noceat exceptio? Neratius, Atilicinus, Proculus, nec siin rem pactus sit, alteri nocere: tantum enim constitutum, ut alter solidum petere possit’ Dig. 2. 14. 27. pr.
